  <h1>Types of Product Defects and Claim Theories</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Auden Cordell (AC), Editor-in-Chief. Contributor: Holland Devlin (HD), Recall &amp; Consumer Safety Reference. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>Every product liability case is built on one or more legal theories. The choice of theory drives what the plaintiff has to prove, what defenses the manufacturer can raise, what expert testimony is needed, and ultimately what the case is worth. This guide explains the three core strict-liability theories (design defect, manufacturing defect, failure to warn) and the companion theories (breach of warranty, consumer fraud) that typically run alongside them.</p>

  <h2>Design defect</h2>

  <p>A design defect exists when the product is unreasonably dangerous as designed. Every unit produced from that design carries the same defect, which is what makes design-defect cases particularly powerful: a finding of defect in one case can support claims by every other person injured by the same product. Two competing tests are used:</p>

  <h3>The consumer-expectation test</h3>

  <p>Originating in California (Greenman v. Yuba Power Products) and adopted in some form by many states, the consumer-expectation test asks whether the product performed as safely as an ordinary consumer would expect when used as intended or in a reasonably foreseeable manner. A car's roof should not collapse in a rollover at survivable speeds. A power tool should not have a switch that can be activated by ordinary bumping. A child's toy should not contain magnets that can be ingested and bind to each other through intestinal tissue. When the product fails an ordinary-consumer expectation, the design is defective.</p>

  <h3>The risk-utility test</h3>

  <p>The competing test, articulated in the Restatement (Third) of Torts: Products Liability &sect; 2(b), asks whether the foreseeable risks of harm posed by the design could have been reduced or avoided by a reasonable alternative design, and whether the omission of the alternative design renders the product not reasonably safe. Practically, this requires the plaintiff to put up an expert who can describe a feasible alternative design that would have prevented the injury. The alternative must be technologically feasible, economically practical, and compatible with the product's intended function.</p>

  <h3>Examples of design-defect cases</h3>

  <p>The Ford Pinto's rear-mounted fuel tank, which would rupture and ignite on moderate rear-end impact &mdash; an alternative design (a rubber bladder, costing approximately $11 per unit) was available and was rejected by the manufacturer for cost reasons. The Bic disposable lighter, which lacked a child-resistant guard at a time when such guards were already available on competitor products. The General Motors C/K-series pickup trucks, with side-saddle fuel tanks vulnerable to side-impact rupture. The Bridgestone-Firestone Wilderness AT tires, which had a tread-separation propensity related to the manufacturing process and the design specification interaction. The certain ATVs that have rollover propensity due to high center of gravity and narrow track width.</p>

  <h2>Manufacturing defect</h2>

  <p>A manufacturing defect exists when one unit, or one batch, deviated from the intended design specification. The defect is not in the design (which may be perfectly reasonable) but in the execution. The plaintiff's prima facie case is conceptually simpler: identify the deviation, tie it to the failure mode, tie the failure mode to the injury.</p>

  <p>Strict liability applies most cleanly to manufacturing defects: even a manufacturer that maintains best-in-class quality-control processes is liable for the individual unit that slipped through. This is a feature, not a bug, of the strict-liability regime &mdash; the policy choice is to put the cost of inevitable manufacturing failures on the manufacturer (which can insure and spread the risk) rather than on the random consumer who happens to receive the defective unit.</p>

  <h3>Examples of manufacturing-defect cases</h3>

  <p>A contaminated drug batch (NDMA contamination in valsartan batches; the Salmonella-contaminated peanut butter cases; the Tylenol cyanide-poisoning case from 1982, which was sabotage rather than manufacturing error but drove the modern tamper-evident packaging requirements). A tire with incomplete vulcanization due to a curing-line malfunction, producing tread separation. An airbag inflator assembled with the wrong propellant grade, producing under- or over-inflation. A medical implant with a surface-finish defect that accelerates wear. A specific batch of helmets with inadequate impact-foam density.</p>

  <h2>Failure to warn (marketing defect)</h2>

  <p>A failure-to-warn claim asserts that the product, even if free of design or manufacturing defects, carried a non-obvious risk that the manufacturer's labeling or instructions did not adequately address. The case turns on three questions:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Was the risk reasonably foreseeable?</strong> The manufacturer's duty is to warn against foreseeable risks, not every conceivable risk.</li>
    <li><strong>Would an adequate warning have prevented the injury?</strong> Causation. If the plaintiff would have ignored the warning anyway, the inadequacy of the warning did not cause the injury. Some states apply a "heeding presumption" that assumes the plaintiff would have followed an adequate warning.</li>
    <li><strong>Was the warning that was given adequate?</strong> Adequacy depends on the prominence, clarity, and specificity of the warning given the user population.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>The learned-intermediary doctrine</h3>

  <p>For prescription drugs and most medical devices, the manufacturer's failure-to-warn duty runs to the prescribing physician, not directly to the patient. The theory is that the physician acts as a "learned intermediary" who evaluates the warnings and makes individual risk-benefit judgments for each patient. This is a significant defense in pharmaceutical cases: the manufacturer is liable for failure to warn the doctor, not for failure to warn the patient. Direct-to-consumer advertising has complicated the doctrine in some states (Perez v. Wyeth Laboratories), which have moved toward direct-to-patient warning duties when the manufacturer markets directly to consumers.</p>

  <h3>Examples of failure-to-warn cases</h3>

  <p>The over-the-counter pain reliever marketed without adequate warning about liver-toxicity interactions with alcohol. The prescription drug marketed without adequate warning about cardiac risk (Vioxx). The dietary supplement marketed without warning about ephedra-related cardiovascular events. The home cleaning product marketed without warning about chlorine-gas formation when mixed with ammonia-containing products. The infant sleeper marketed without warning about the suffocation risk from incline-sleep position. The lithium-battery-powered device marketed without warning about thermal-runaway risk if punctured or short-circuited.</p>

  <h2>Breach of warranty</h2>

  <p>Two types of warranty claims commonly run alongside strict-liability counts:</p>

  <h3>Express warranty</h3>

  <p>The manufacturer made a specific representation about the product &mdash; "Rated to 500 lbs of dynamic load," "Guaranteed leak-proof to 30 meters," "FDA-approved for migraine prevention," "Will not shatter at temperatures down to -40&deg;F" &mdash; the representation was false, and the falsity caused harm. Express-warranty claims are often the easiest to plead and prove because the false statement is documented in the manufacturer's own marketing.</p>

  <h3>Implied warranty of merchantability</h3>

  <p>Under UCC &sect; 2-314, every product sold in the ordinary course carries an implied warranty that it is fit for its ordinary purpose. A car is impliedly warranted to run; a knife is impliedly warranted to cut without breaking; a child's toy is impliedly warranted to be safe for ordinary play. The implied warranty can be disclaimed in commercial transactions between merchants (with specific language) but generally cannot be disclaimed in consumer sales. Magnuson-Moss Warranty Act adds federal protections for consumer-product warranties.</p>

  <h2>Consumer fraud and unfair trade practices</h2>

  <p>Most states have consumer-protection statutes that prohibit deceptive marketing of consumer products and allow private rights of action, often with statutory damages and attorney's fees. California's Consumer Legal Remedies Act and Unfair Competition Law are the most-used; New York's General Business Law &sect; 349; Massachusetts Chapter 93A; and parallel statutes in essentially every state. These claims are particularly useful in class actions because statutory damages do not require individual injury proof, only deception.</p>

  <h2>Choosing among theories</h2>

  <p>An experienced product liability lawyer will often plead two or three of these theories in the alternative. The strict-liability counts (design, manufacturing, failure to warn) carry the bulk of the damages exposure. The warranty and consumer-fraud counts add procedural advantages (statutory fee-shifting, lower causation burdens) and capture residual exposure if the strict-liability theory fails. The downside of pleading multiple theories is added discovery scope; the upside is multiple paths to liability and stronger settlement leverage.</p>

